        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "LLMs can produce outputs that are syntactically correct but functionally broken: a response that repeats the same sentence forty times, a JSON payload that fails to parse, an answer that bears no relation to the question, or a confident statement of a fact that never happened. These are "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "italic"
              }
            ],
            "text": "degenerate outputs"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " — not errors from the API, but failures in the content itself. Unlike a timeout (which you can catch by exception), degenerate outputs require explicit validation logic on the application side."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "Five degenerate output types: repetition loop, hallucination, schema violation, truncated output, and incoherence — each with detection signals and recovery strategies. Bottom row shows a common 5-step detection pipeline."
        }
      },
